      "title"			: "No Cross-hatching in Ggplot2",
      "link"			: "http://hywel.github.io/blog/no-cross-hatching-in-ggplot2/",
      "excerpt"		: "<p>After some very brief <a href="http://stackoverflow.com/questions/2895319/how-to-add-texture-to-fill-colors-in-ggplot2?lq=1">web searching</a>, I have reached the conclusion that it is currently not possible to apply cross-hatching effects to the fill in a <code class="highlighter-rouge">ggplot</code>.</p>

<p>My rather crude solution was to add this in a graphics package<sup id="fnref:1"><a href="#fn:1" class="footnote">1</a></sup>. Selecting each of the bars, including the box within the key, then applying a “half-tone” filter in a new layer. Once the effect is applyed the opacity can be reduced in the hatching layer.</p>

<p><img src="/figures/Figure_6_modified.png" alt="Figure" /></p>

<p>The figure above will appear in [Blythe et al., 2016]<sup id="fnref:2"><a href="#fn:2" class="footnote">2</a></sup>.</p>

<h3 id="references">References</h3>
<p>Blythe, J., Mardigan, K. C., Perdjert, M. E., and Stoakes, H. (2016). Pointing out directions in Murrinhpatha. <em>Open Linguistics</em>, In Press.</p>

<div class="footnotes">
  <ol>
    <li id="fn:1">
      <p>I used <a href="http://www.pixelmator.com/mac/"><em>Pixelmator</em></a> on OS X but any similar tool would work <a href="#fnref:1" class="reversefootnote">&#8617;</a></p>
    </li>
    <li id="fn:2">
      <p>I am investigating ways to parse references but this was inserted manually. <a href="#fnref:2" class="reversefootnote">&#8617;</a></p>
    </li>
  </ol>
</div>
"
